LE02. Lower section of Baldwin is spring fed (Darrah Springs) and is a perennial stream, the upper section of Baldwin Creek is an intermittent stream.  PG&E once diverted water from creek to the Coleman Canal, however, this diversion hasn't taken place in sometime (not sure how long but at least 3-4 years).

LE03. Inskip = Mix of SF (think South Fork Battle Ck) and Ripley Creek water. I was under the impression that Ripley was a perennial stream, but we had a Thermal Infrared survey flown last summer and it was dry.  The section flown was below Lower Ripley Dam, so there is potential that all water from the creek was being diverted.  This water is diverted to Inskip Canal and Inskip Powerhouse.  The Inskip tailrace (powerhouse release) is approximately 0.1 miles from the start of the Coleman Canal.
